      "title": "Module 1 — The conditioning began before your first cigarette",
      "text": "From childhood you absorbed thousands of images and messages quietly teaching that the cigarette delivers something real: the calm character lighting up after a hard day, the cool rebel, the sophisticate, the soldier steadying his nerves, the friends bonding over a shared smoke. Advertising spent generations and fortunes welding cigarettes to relaxation, freedom, maturity, and belonging. None of it was true — but by the time you tried your first one, your mind was already pre-loaded to interpret the experience as pleasure and coping.\n\nThis is why that first cigarette is such a strange initiation. It tasted awful. Your body coughed and recoiled — its honest verdict was this is poison. But the brainwashing was stronger than the evidence in your own lungs, so you pushed through the disgust and worked hard to become a smoker. That's worth sitting with: you had to overcome your body's clear warning, because your mind had already been told the prize was worth it."
